    "reasoning": "The PostgreSQL query execution pipeline is organized in distinct stages with clear data structure transformations:\n\n**Parsing Stage (scan.l + gram.y + parser.c):**\nThe lexer (flex, scan.l) tokenizes the SQL string into a stream of tokens. The grammar (bison, gram.y) reduces these tokens using shift-reduce parsing to produce an abstract syntax tree. The raw_parser() function in parser.c orchestrates this by initializing the flex scanner and bison parser, returning a list of RawStmt nodes. RawStmt is a simple wrapper containing the statement node (SelectStmt, InsertStmt, etc.) and location information.\n\n**Analysis & Rewriting Stage (analyze.c + rewrite/):**\nThe semantic analyzer (parse_analyze_fixedparams in analyze.c) transforms each RawStmt into a Query node through multiple passes:\n- Name resolution: tables, columns, functions\n- Type inference and coercion\n- Predicate pushing and qualification processing\n- Aggregate and window function detection\nThis produces a normalized Query structure. The rewriter (QueryRewrite in rewriteHandler.c) then applies rules - transforming views into their base query and applying INSTEAD rules for triggers. Output is a list of Query nodes, potentially expanded from a single input.\n\n**Two-Phase Optimization (planner.c, allpaths.c, createplan.c):**\nThe optimizer implements a classic two-phase approach:\nPhase 1 (Path Generation - allpaths.c):\n- For each base table, enumerate all applicable access methods (sequential scan, index scans, bitmap scans) creating Paths\n- For each table, precompute selectivity estimates and potential parameterizations\n- Build a RelOptInfo structure for each base table and each possible join combination\n- Use dynamic programming to systematically consider all join orderings\n- For each join pair, generate Paths for each join method (nested loop, merge join, hash join)\n- Maintain a Pareto-optimal set of Paths based on cost estimates (different Paths may be optimal for different output orderings or row counts)\n\nPhase 2 (Plan Creation - createplan.c):\n- Select the cheapest Path for the final RelOptInfo (covering all relations)\n- Call create_plan() recursively to convert the Path tree into a Plan tree\n- This process selects specific operators and fills in execution parameters\n- The result is a Plan tree that mirrors the Path tree structure\n- Wrap the Plan in a PlannedStmt which contains metadata for execution (parameter types, resource relations, etc.)\n\n**Executor Stage (execProcnode.c, execMain.c):**\nThe executor implements a Volcano-style pull-based pipeline:\nInitialization (ExecInitNode):\n- ExecInitNode() dispatches on Plan node type (via switch statement)\n- For each Plan node type (SeqScan, NestLoop, Agg, etc.), calls the corresponding ExecInit* function\n- This creates a parallel tree of PlanState nodes that mirror the Plan tree\n- PlanState nodes hold runtime state while Plan nodes remain read-only\n- Each node is initialized recursively, building the entire state tree bottom-up\n\nExecution (ExecProcNode):\n- ExecProcNode() is called repeatedly on the root PlanState\n- This macro/function uses either function pointers or a dispatch table\n- Each node type implements an ExecXxx function (ExecSeqScan, ExecNestLoop, etc.)\n- Each function produces the next tuple by calling ExecProcNode on child nodes\n- Child nodes are called in a demand-pull model - parents request tuples as needed\n- When a child is exhausted (returns NULL), the parent adjusts its iteration\n- Tuples flow up the tree as TupleTableSlot pointers\n\n**Data Structure Transformations:**\nSQL String → RawStmt (parsing) → Query (analysis/rewrite) → Path nodes & RelOptInfo (optimization phase 1) → Plan nodes in PlannedStmt (optimization phase 2) → PlanState tree mirroring Plan tree (execution initialization) → Tuples via ExecProcNode dispatch (execution).\n\n**Design Patterns Identified:**\n1. Volcano Architecture: Pull-based pipeline where parent nodes request t